content: The task is to control the ground traffic on an airport (in such a way that the summed up travel time of all airplanes is minimised). Timed travel routes must be assigned to the airplanes so that they reach their targets. There is inbound traffic  (planes that need to go to a parking position) and outbound traffic (planes that need to go to a runway). The former are airplanes that must take off, the latter are airplanes that have just landed and have to park.  The main problem constraint is to ensure the safety of the airplanes. This means to avoid collisions, and also to prevent airplanes from entering the unsafe zones behind large airplanes that have their engines running. Which means that no two planes can share the same airport segment, and that a plane with running engines blocks a set of segments behind it (where the blocked set depends on the size category of the plane). The available activities are to move a plane away backwards from a parking position, to startup the engines, to move between segments, to park by turning off the engines, and to remove the plane from the airport.  The criterion is to minimize the summed up travel time (on the surface of the airport) of all airplanes. There usually are standard routes, i.e., routes that any airplane must take when outbound from a certain parking area, or inbound from a certain runway. The reason for introducing such routes is to reduce complexity for human ground controllers, since significant computer support is not yet available at real airports.
